A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly inappropriate system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Second, in the face of this system's ineffectiveness, populist actors continue to exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required nearly 70 years of intense effort.
This is why it is essential that such an active approach be undertaken this year at both the European and global levels.
In September, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to engage concretely and sustainably.
This necessary engagement was tragically lacking in 2015.
Indeed, if the international community had provided even the smallest amount of support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host nearly four million refugees, it would have been able to mitigate last year's crisis.
With around 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better equipped to house, feed, and educate the refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion euros every year in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are far outweighed by its human and political costs.
More than one million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, only to endure a exhausting journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing them asylum.
The most cynical politicians have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting a hateful nationalist narrative that either ignores or distorts the migrant experience.
In the United States, for example, not one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist activity.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigrant parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also encourages traditional parties to promote a hostile immigration policy as well.
This situation has considerably undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million of refugees arriving on its shores only managed to "relocate" 190 of them.
Border controls have been reinstated in six Schengen area countries, at least temporarily.
To the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis is not just about Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographic proximity.
Nevertheless, the EU likely faces today a threat to its very existence, which it can overcome only by demonstrating firmly the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The highest priority must be to establish legal and secure pathways for refugees to reach Europe.
This is not to say that every migrant in need should be welcomed.
It remains, however, for the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to use orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would protect migrants while safeguarding Europe (through the ability to fully examine applications).
Beyond a approach aimed at discouraging asylum seekers from risking their lives crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to these efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a robust global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will primarily require more countries to accept hosting refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has only been able to resettle less than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Many of them end up in a state of prolonged migration, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, trapped in a sort of limbo and uncertain about the day they might return home.
In 2016, developed countries must agree to annually host a cumulative number close to one million refugees, either through resettlement or by granting humanitarian, student, professional, or other visas.
With Canada having pledged to welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this goal is clearly achievable.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current situation, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, healthcare, education, and vocational training during the initial years of resettlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering under the strain of the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, job market, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if countries in Europe and beyond overcome their prejudices against migrants.
If these individuals continue to be seen as a burden, or even a threat to security, reactionary political forces will keep gaining ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if hosting states manage to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, everyone benefits – including those countries (among others through financial inflows).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved it could subordinate its national interests to a broader global objective: fighting climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
